         <abstract>
            <p>Let $\Omega^c$ be the complementary of a bounded regular domain in $R^2$ of boundary $\Gamma$. We consider the problem \begin{equation*}\tag{1} \begin{cases}\Delta u = f;\quad \text{ in } \Omega^c, \\ u\mid_\Gamma = u_0,\end{cases}\end{equation*} where $f$ has its support in a bounded subdomain $\Omega_1$ of $\Omega^c$. Let $\Gamma_2$ be the common boundary of $\Omega_1$ and $\Omega_2 = \Omega^c - \Omega_1$. We solve the problem (1) by using an equivalent system of equations involving an integral equation on $\Gamma_2$ coupled with the equation: \begin{equation*}\tag{2} \begin{cases}\Delta u = f\quad \text{ in } \Omega_1, \\ u\mid_\Gamma = u_0, \\ u\mid_{\Gamma_2} = \lambda.\end{cases}\end{equation*} We introduce a finite element approximation of Eq. (2) and of the integral equation and we prove optimal error estimates.</p>
